    walk: `When trouble comes, friend, the first thing we usually do is look around for help. We scan the horizon — money, people, our own strength, a plan — searching for something to save us. This Psalm begins the same way: I will lift up mine eyes unto the hills. The traveler looks to the hills, wondering where help will come from on a dangerous road.

But then the psalmist lifts his eyes higher. My help cometh from the LORD, which made heaven and earth. Not from the hills themselves. Not from his own resources. From the One who made it all. When you don't know where to turn, this is the answer: your help comes from God — the same God who flung the stars into place and set the mountains on their foundations.

Think about that for a moment. The God you're asking for help is not running low on power. He made heaven and earth. There is no problem in your life too big for the hands that shaped the universe, and no problem too small for the heart that numbers the hairs on your head.

The rest of Psalm 121 is full of promises: He will not let your foot be moved; He never sleeps; He keeps you in your going out and your coming in. He is a God who watches over you with unwearied attention, day and night.

So when you feel overwhelmed today, friend, don't just look around — look up. Lift your eyes past the problem to the Maker of heaven and earth. Your help has a name, and He is watching over you even now.`,
    prayer: `Father, when I'm overwhelmed and searching for help, remind me to lift my eyes to You. You made heaven and earth — nothing is too hard for You. Thank You that You never sleep, that You watch over my coming and going. I put my trust in You today. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `The next time worry rises today, physically lift your eyes upward for a moment and say, "My help comes from the Lord, who made heaven and earth."`,
