    walk: `David wrote this Psalm in a cave, friend, hiding for his life, feeling utterly alone. Earlier in the very same Psalm he says the loneliest words: no man cared for my soul. Maybe you've felt that — that ache of being overlooked, unseen, like no one would notice if you disappeared. It's one of the heaviest burdens a heart can carry.

And yet, even in that lonely cave, even when he felt that no person cared, David turns to God and says: Thou art my refuge and my portion in the land of the living. When human comfort failed him completely, he found that God had not. The cave was lonely, but it was not empty. God was there.

There's something this loneliest week of the Psalms wants you to see: even when you feel forgotten by everyone, God still cares for your soul. The very moment David felt most alone, he discovered God as his refuge — his shelter — and his portion — his inheritance, the thing that was truly his. When everything and everyone else is stripped away, God remains, and He is enough.

This doesn't mean human friendship doesn't matter; God made us for one another, and isolation is a hard road. But it does mean that even in the seasons when people fail you, when no one seems to understand, when the cave feels lonely and dark — you are not actually alone. There is One who sees you, who knows your name, who cares for your soul more tenderly than any person ever could.

So if you feel unseen today, friend, cry out like David did. Tell God you feel alone — He can take it. And then remember: Thou art my refuge and my portion. He is with you in the cave. You are not forgotten.`,
    prayer: `Father, in the moments I feel alone and unseen, when it seems no one cares for my soul, remind me that You do. You are my refuge and my portion. Thank You that even in the loneliest cave, You are with me. Be my comfort and my companion today. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `If loneliness presses on you today, speak David's words aloud: "Thou art my refuge and my portion in the land of the living." And consider reaching out to one person, too — God often sends His care through others.`,
    reflect: `When have you felt that "no one cared for your soul"? How does it comfort you to know God is your refuge and portion even then?`,
