    walk: `After two weeks of pouring out our hearts, friend, the Psalms begin to turn — and so does this verse. It doesn't deny the weeping. It doesn't pretend the night isn't real. Weeping may endure for a night. God's Word is honest about sorrow; there are nights of tears, and some of them are long. But the verse doesn't end in the dark. Joy cometh in the morning.

Hold on to the shape of that promise. The night is real — but it is a night, not an endless dark. Nights end. Morning comes. For the child of God, weeping is never the final chapter; it is a season that gives way to joy. The sorrow may feel like it will last forever when you're in it, but God says otherwise. Morning is coming.

Look at the contrast David draws. His anger endureth but a moment; in his favour is life. Whatever hard thing you're walking through, it is momentary compared to the life and favor God has for you. The trouble feels enormous and the night feels long, but weighed against eternity in God's favor, this present sorrow is a passing thing. The morning outlasts the night by forever.

This is what trust does, friend: it lets you hold on through the night because you believe in the morning. You don't have to manufacture joy you don't feel right now. You only have to trust the One who promises that joy is on its way — that He turns mourning into dancing, that He has not abandoned you to the dark.

If you're in a night of weeping today, don't lose heart. Tears are not the end of your story. Keep trusting. Keep holding on. Joy cometh in the morning, and your morning is coming.`,
    prayer: `Father, thank You that weeping endures only for a night, but joy comes in the morning. When my nights feel long, help me trust that morning is coming. You turn mourning into dancing. I hold on to Your promise of joy today, even before I feel it. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `If you're in a hard season, write down or speak this promise today: "Joy cometh in the morning." Let it be an anchor of hope you return to when the night feels long.`,
